Figure Caption: XRD patterns from the as-cast (FeCoNiCrMn)100−xAlx(Alx) samples indicate a phase transition from fcc to bcc starting at ∼Al8.

Details of (111)fccand (110)bccpeak shifting in as-cast Alxalloys: (a) Al0–Al10, (b) Al11–Al20. A discernible minor peak arises in Al8at 2θ≈40°, indicating the presence of a small volume of bcc phase.
SEM micrographs of etched as-cast Alxalloys: (a) is a secondary-electron image of Al0and (b–k) are backscattered images for Al4–Al20, respectively.

Mechanical properties of the as-cast Alxalloys at room temperature: (a) engineering stress–strain curves of Alx, (b) tensile strength, yield strength and elongation as a function of Al and (c) Vickers hardness variation with the Al content.
The value of VEC as a function of the Al content in (FeCoNiCrMn)100−xAlxalloys.
Lattice constant of (FeCoNiCrMn)100−xAlxalloys as a function of the Al content. Solid squares and triangles represent the fcc and bcc phases, respectively.

(a) The volume fraction of bcc (Vbcc) as a function of Al measured by the grid method, and (b) the nearly linear relationship betweenVbccand the tensile fracture strength (σ) when the Al content is within 8–11%.

TEM images of Al8, Al11, Al13, Al16and Al20alloys. Bright-field images are shown in (a), (c), (e), (g) and (i), respectively, while the corresponding dark-field images in the same region are shown in (b), (d), (f), (h) and (j).
